1. To prove that the equation $f(x)=2$ has exactly one real root, it is equivalent to proving that $g(x)=e^{x}+\cos x-2=0$ has exactly one zero point;
2. Find the derivative of $g(x)$: $g'(x)=e^{x}-\sin x$, let $h(x)=g'(x)$, find the derivative of $h(x)$: $h'(x)=e^{x}-\cos x$;
3. Discuss in intervals: ① When $x>0$, $h'(x)>e^{0}-\cos x=1-\cos x\geq0$, so $h(x)$ is monotonically increasing on $(0, +\infty)$, $h(x)>h(0)=1$, that is $g'(x)>0$, $g(x)$ is monotonically increasing on $(0, +\infty)$, $g(x)>g(0)=0$, no zero point; ② When $x=0$, $g(0)=0$, there is one zero point; ③ When $x<0$, $g(x)=e^{x}+\cos x-2<e^{0}+\cos x-2=-1+\cos x\leq0$, no zero point;
4. Synthesize the situations of the three intervals, $g(x)$ has exactly one zero point, that is the equation $f(x)=2$ has exactly one real root.

